==English==

===Etymology===
From the Ancient Greek proverb ''γλαυκ̀ εὶς ̀Αθήνας'' (glauk eis Athenas).  The owl was the symbol of the city of [[w:Athens|Athens]], and was sacred to its patron goddess, [[w:Athena|Athena]], and thus was easy to find in Athens.  In addition, the owl was featured on Athens' silver coins, and Athens both mined its own silver and minted its own coins.  Therefore, bringing owls (either the real birds, or the coins) to Athens would be pointless.

===Proverb===
'''[[owl|owls]] [[to]] [[Athens]]'''
# A pointless [[venture]], one that is [[redundant]], [[unnecessary]], [[superfluous]], or highly [[stupid|uneconomical]].  Cf. ''[[coals to Newcastle]]''.
#* ''Who brings owls to Athens?'' - Euelpides, in Aristophanes' ''Birds'' ([http://www.mala.bc.ca/~johnstoi/aristophanes/birds.htm English translation by Ian Johnston])
#* ''Forgive me, then, for bringing owls to Athens as a thanks-offering.'' - Goethe, in a letter to Wilhelm von Humboldt ([http://www.gutenberg.org/files/11366/11366-8.txt English translation by Louis H. Gray])
#* ''Perhaps we have not been sufficiently aware that talking about access and its implications in Scandinavia is like bringing owls to Athens.'' - Herbert Burkert ([http://europa.eu.int/ISPO/legal/stockholm/en/burkert.html])

